description : The current Nature Breakdown capability identifies high-level intent types but does not consistently recognize the contextual role of the request—such as whether the user is asking for clinical information extraction, analytical interpretation, document understanding, or workflow support.

This user story enhances the Nature Breakdown logic to explicitly identify, and label contextual information associated with an incoming request. Contextual identification enables the system to distinguish between direct clinical inquiries and meta-level clinical operations/environment (e.g.,  temporal, location, indication etc.) while maintaining strict boundaries against non-clinical use cases.

By incorporating contextual signals into the Nature Breakdown output, downstream systems (intent extraction, routing, safety checks, and response generation) can make more informed decisions about how to process clinically relevant requests, improving accuracy, usability, and alignment with real-world ODE workflows.

This capability builds on the refined intent extraction behavior by ensuring that why and how a request is being made is explicitly captured, not just what clinical domain it touches.

Dev Note:


At the moment, we limit use of this capability within clinical domain. The relax version is slated for future expansion.
This story focuses on method development, rather than API.

Acceptance criteria  : 
Method outputs information types that indicate/confirm finding of information
The Nature Breakdown API correctly identifies the contextual environment of clinically relevant requests (e.g., temporal, location, indication, etc.)
Context labels align with the extracted intent and support downstream routing and processing.
Clinically relevant meta and workflow-oriented requests are accepted and correctly classified.
Requests that are entirely non-clinical continue to be rejected.
Contextual information is returned using the standardized Nature Breakdown output without breaking existing consumers.
Test cases confirm previously rejected clinical meta-requests now pass, while non-clinical requests still fail.
Unit test
Document the method
